This is a tricky one.  From [the documentation of the XPath class](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.xml/javax/xml/xpath/XPath.html):

&gt; This result of evaluating an expression is converted to an instance of the desired return type. Valid return types are defined in XPathConstants. Conversion to the return type follows XPath conversion rules.

Since you’re converting to a string, the “XPath conversion rules” come from [section 3.2](https://www.w3.org/TR/1999/REC-xpath-19991116/#section-Function-Calls) of the XPath specification:

&gt;An argument is converted to type string as if by calling the string function.

And [the string() function](https://www.w3.org/TR/1999/REC-xpath-19991116/#function-string) is documented thus:

&gt;A node-set is converted to a string by returning the string-value of the node in the node-set that is first in document order. If the node-set is empty, an empty string is returned.

The text() node that is first in document order is the whitespace between the `&lt;div class=history-value&quot;&gt;` tag and the start of the span tag;  specifically, `&quot;\n                &quot;`.  As the documentation says, only that first text node is evaluated as a string, even though `/text()` matches more than one text child.

A workaround is to examine the text children yourself.  Replace this:

    result_divValues = expr_divValues.evaluate(doxDiv, XPathConstants.STRING);

with this:

